name: cis-1-bromo-1-heptene
source: Dreisbach R. R. Physical Properties of Chemical Compounds; Vol. III; American Chemical Society; Washington; 1961.
Reason: The base unit for the compound is ethene, which has a melting point of -169.2 degrees Celsius. Each additional methylene (-CH2-) group in aliphatic hydrocarbons generally raises the melting point by approximately +2 degrees Celsius due to an increase in van der Waals forces. With five extra methylene groups in the compound, this would add roughly +10 degrees Celsius. The cis double bond tends to lower the melting point in comparison to a trans double bond or an alkane, so it could have a decreasing effect of about -5 degrees Celsius. The bromine atom is a large, heavy atom that significantly raises the melting point due to increased van der Waals forces. We can estimate the increase to be around +20 degrees Celsius, taking into account its large mass relative to hydrogen. Combining these effects: base ethene value (-169.2) + methylene groups (+10) + bromine (+20) - cis double bond effect (-5), we arrive at an estimated melting point.
